  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">RCRSS_Integrated Community Action for Nutrition in the 1st 1000 days (ICAN-1000)-TUBAKUZE</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">- Improved health outcomes in Nutrition; HIV, MCH and Malaria
- Capacity building to improve knowledge on nutrition
- Awareness on social norms identified as barriers for the improvement of nutrition outcomes  within community
- Implement community approach(CG) to reach easily our target (Pregnant and lactating women) 
- Initiate hospitals baby-friendly
- Promote best practices for maternal and child health
- Support MoH on identified issues related to access to nutrition services and MCH	 
- Awareness on stigma and discrimination reduction related to HIV in collaboration with RLs
- Advocacy to inform policy and plans  related to health issues/rights of women, children and PLWHIV at national and community level
- Use PVCA to assess community capacity and vulnerabilities 
- Promote best practices for maternal and child health
- Support MoH on identified issues related to access to nutrition services and MCH	 
- Awareness on stigma and discrimination reduction related to HIV in collaboration with RLs
- Advocacy to inform policy and plans  related to health issues/rights of women, children and PLWHIV at national and community level</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. IMPROVED HEALTH OUTCOMES IN NUTRITION; HIV, MCH AND MALARIA
1.1. Improved Knowledge on nutrition
1.2. Increased understanding of the influence of social norms on nutrition outcomes (within community)
1.3. Improved health services in zone of intervention
2. REDUCING HIV STIGMA AND DISCRIMINATION AND CHANGING SOCIAL NORMS THAT ARE HARMFUL TO HEALTH SUCH (INCLUDING GENDER AND POWER DYNAMICS)
2.1. Improved knowledge, attitudes and practices on Stigma and discrimination of PLWHIV within fait based organization and the community  
2.1. Improved policy and plans related to health issues/rights of women, children and PLWHIV at national and community level</narrative>
  </description>
